SIMPLE: gypsy
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Gypsy
<hw>Gyp"sy</hw> <pr>(j⟦icr⟧p"s⟦ycr⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>;
<plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Gypsies</plw> <pr>(j⟦icr⟧p"s⟦icr⟧z)</pr>.</plu>
<ety>[OE. <ets>Gypcyan</ets>, F. <ets>⟦eacute⟧gyptien</ets> Egyptian,
gypsy, L. <ets>Aegyptius</ets>. See <er>Egyptian</er>.]</ety>
<altsp>[Also spelled <asp>gipsy</asp> and <asp>gypsey</asp>.]</altsp>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>One of a vagabond race, whose tribes, coming originally
from India, entered Europe in the 14th or 15th century, and are now
scattered over Turkey, Russia, Hungary, Spain, England, etc., living by
theft, fortune telling, horsejockeying, tinkering, etc. Cf.
<er>Bohemian</er>, <er>Romany</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Like a right <qex>gypsy</qex>, hath, at fast and loose,⟦br⟧
Beguiled me to the very heart of loss.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The language used by the gypsies.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A dark-complexioned person.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A cunning or crafty person.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark> <rj><au>Prior.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gypsy</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Gypsy
<hw>Gyp"sy</hw> <pos>a.</pos> <def>Pertaining to, or suitable for,
gypsies.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Gypsy hat</b></col>, <cd>a woman's or child's
broad-brimmed hat, usually of straw or felt.</cd> -- <col><b>Gypsy
winch</b></col>, <cd>a small winch, which may be operated by a crank, or
by a ratchet and pawl through a lever working up and down.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 661 pr=JMD --></p>

<p><ent>Gypsy</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Gypsy
<hw>Gyp"sy</hw> <pr>(j⟦icr⟧p"s⟦ycr⟧)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To play
the gypsy; to picnic in the woods.</def> <wordforms><mark>Mostly</mark>,
<wf>Gyp"sy*ing</wf>, <pos>vb. n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gypsyism</ent>⟦br⟧
